Let $f(x) = \frac{2x+9}{x-7}.$ Find the product of all solutions to the equation $f(f(x)) = x.$
inference:
Let $f(x) = \frac{2x+9}{x-7}$.
We want to solve $f(f(x)) = x$.
$$f(f(x)) = f\left(\frac{2x+9}{x-7}\right) = \frac{2\left(\frac{2x+9}{x-7}\right) + 9}{\frac{2x+9}{x-7} - 7} = \frac{\frac{2(2x+9) + 9(x-7)}{x-7}}{\frac{2x+9 - 7(x-7)}{x-7}} = \frac{\frac{4x+18+9x-63}{x-7}}{\frac{2x+9-7x+49}{x-7}} = \frac{13x-45}{-5x+58} = x$$
$$13x-45 = x(-5x+58)$$
$$13x-45 = -5x^2 + 58x$$
$$5x^2 - 45x - 45 = 0$$
Dividing by 5,
$$x^2 - 9x - 9 = 0$$
Using the quadratic formula,
$$x = \frac{9 \pm \sqrt{81 - 4(1)(-9)}}{2} = \frac{9 \pm \sqrt{81+36}}{2} = \frac{9 \pm \sqrt{117}}{2} = \frac{9 \pm 3\sqrt{13}}{2}$$
The solutions are $x = \frac{9 + 3\sqrt{13}}{2}$ and $x = \frac{9 - 3\sqrt{13}}{2}$.
The product of the solutions is $\frac{9+3\sqrt{13}}{2}\frac{9-3\sqrt{13}}{2} = \frac{81 - 3^2(13)}{4} = \frac{81 - 117}{4} = \frac{-36}{4} = -9$
Final Answer: $\boxed{-9}$
ground_truth: We have \[\begin{aligned} f(f(x)) &= f\left(\frac{2x+9}{x-7}\right) \\ &= \frac{2 \cdot \frac{2x+9}{x-7} + 9}{\frac{2x+9}{x-7} - 7} \\ &= \frac{2(2x+9) + 9(x-7)}{(2x+9) - 7(x-7)} \\ &= \frac{13x - 45}{-5x + 58}.\end{aligned}\]Therefore, the equation $f(f(x)) = x$ becomes \[13x - 45 = -5x^2 + 58x,\]or \[5x^2 - 45x - 45 = 0.\]By Vieta's formulas, the product of the solutions to this equation is $\frac{-45}{5},$ or $\boxed{-9}.$
